* Annotation 3: @SuppressWarnings

1. "What is @SuppressWarnings?"

➡ It is a built-in annotation in Java.

➡ It tells the compiler:
  👉 “Ignore certain warnings in this part of the code.”

➡ It does not remove errors (only warnings).


2. "Why do we need it?"

➡ Sometimes the compiler shows warnings even if the code is safe or intentional.

➡ Too many warnings = clutter, harder to see real issues.

➡ @SuppressWarnings helps hide specific warnings that you don’t want to see.


3. "Where can we use it?"

   * We can apply it on:
     ➡ Class
     ➡ Method
     ➡ Field (variable)
     ➡ Constructor
     ➡ Local variable
     ➡ Parameter

Basically, almost anywhere you write code.


4. Common Warning Types (Arguments)

   Argument	                   Meaning
"deprecation"	Ignore warnings for deprecated methods/classes
"unchecked"  	Ignore unchecked type cast warnings (mainly with generics)
"rawtypes"   	Ignore warnings when using raw types (like List instead of List<String>)
"serial"    	Ignore missing serialVersionUID warning in Serializable classes
"unused"	    Ignore unused variables, parameters, or methods
"all"       	Ignore all warnings (⚠ Dangerous, not recommended)


6. Examples for Each Type

(a) "deprecation"
class OldCode {
    @Deprecated
    void oldMethod() {}
}

class Test {
    @SuppressWarnings("deprecation")
    void demo() {
        OldCode obj = new OldCode();
        obj.oldMethod(); // Warning hidden
    }
}

(b) "unchecked"
import java.util.*;

class Test {
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    void demo() {
        List list = new ArrayList(); // Raw type, unsafe
        list.add("Hello");
        List<String> strList = list; // Normally gives unchecked warning
    }
}

(c) "rawtypes"
import java.util.*;

class Test {
    @SuppressWarnings("rawtypes")
    void demo() {
        List list = new ArrayList(); // Using raw List
        list.add(10);
    }
}

(d) "serial"
import java.io.*;

@SuppressWarnings("serial")
class MyClass implements Serializable {
    // Normally, compiler warns: “Add serialVersionUID”
}

(e) "unused"
class Test {
    @SuppressWarnings("unused")
    private int data; // Compiler warns normally: "Variable never used"
}

(f) "all"
@SuppressWarnings("all")
class Test {
    private int data; // unused
    void demo() {
        List list = new ArrayList(); // raw + unchecked
    }
}


7. Multiple Warnings Together

We can suppress multiple warnings by using { }:
@SuppressWarnings({"rawtypes", "unchecked"})
class Test {
    void demo() {
        List list = new ArrayList();  // raw + unchecked
        List<String> strList = list;  // unchecked
    }
}